    "body": "### Problem\n\nWith `ui2` enabled and `cmdheight=0`, pressing `:` to open the command line shifts the buffer viewport up by one line. The viewport does **not** revert after leaving cmdline mode — the scroll persists.\n\nThe scroll occurs only when the bottom window row is a buffer row (including empty buffer rows). If the bottom row shows a `~` empty-buffer filler, no scroll occurs.\n\nWithout `ui2` enabled, this does not happen under identical conditions.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```bash\nnvim --clean --cmd \"set cmdheight=0 laststatus=0\" --cmd \"lua require('vim._core.ui2').enable({})\"\n```\n\nOn the startup screen:\n\n1. Press `i` to enter insert mode.\n2. Press `<Enter>` repeatedly until no `~` tildes are visible at the bottom of the window.\n3. Press `<Esc>` to return to normal mode.\n4. Press `:`  the buffer content shifts up by one line.\n5. Press `<Esc>` the viewport remains shifted.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nEntering cmdline mode should not shift the buffer viewport. `ui2` renders the cmdline as a floating window, so it should overlay, not displace buffer content.\n\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-nightly+451811b Build type: Release LuaJIT 2.1.1741730670 Run \"nvim -V1 -v\" for more info\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A — `ui2` is Nvim-specific.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nNixOS 26.05 (Yarara) x86_64\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty Version 0.17.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nBuilt from source via `nix build github:nix-community/neovim-nightly-overlay --override-input neovim-src .`",
